	abstract = {Recent advances in remote sensing and ecological modeling warrant a timely and robust investigation{\textbackslash}n of the ecological variables that underlie large-scale patterns of breeding bird species richness,{\textbackslash}n particularly in the context of intensifying land use and climate change. Our objective was to{\textbackslash}n address this need using an array of bioclimatic and remotely sensed data sets representing{\textbackslash}n vegetation properties and structure, and other aspects of the physical environment. We first build{\textbackslash}n models of bird species richness across breeding bird survey (BBS) routes, and then spatially predict{\textbackslash}n richness across the coterminous US at moderately high spatial resolution (1 km). Predictor variables{\textbackslash}n were derived from various sources and maps of species richness were generated for four groups{\textbackslash}n (guilds) of birds with different breeding habitat affiliation (forest, grassland, open woodland,{\textbackslash}n scrub/shrub), as well as all guilds combined. Predictions of forest bird distributions were strong ({\textbackslash}n R 2 = 0.85), followed by grassland (0.76), scrub/shrub (0.63) and open woodland (0.60) species.{\textbackslash}n Vegetation properties were generally the strongest determinants of species richness, whereas{\textbackslash}n bioclimatic and lidar-derived vertical structure metrics were of variable importance and dependent{\textbackslash}n upon the guild type. Environmental variables (climate and the physical environment) were also{\textbackslash}n frequently selected predictors, but canopy structure variables were not as important as expected{\textbackslash}n based on more local to regional scale studies. Relatively sparse sampling of canopy structure{\textbackslash}n metrics from the satellite lidar sensor may have reduced their importance relative to other{\textbackslash}n predictor variables across the study domain. We discuss these results in the context of the{\textbackslash}n ecological drivers of species richness patterns, the spatial scale of bird diversity analyses, and{\textbackslash}n the potential of next generation space-borne lidar systems relevant to vegetation and ecosystem{\textbackslash}n studies. This study strengthens current understanding of bird species–climate–vegetation{\textbackslash}n relationships, which could be further advanced with improved canopy structure information across{\textbackslash}n spatial scales.},
	number = {3},
